KW  - numerical simulation
AB  - If a landslide is triggered by the ascent of groundwater within the earth mass that starts moving, the shear stress induced at the slip surface may cause a chain reaction of liquefaction from the bottom to upper within the saturated layer. The solid earth block part, supported by the pore pressure in the successively produced liquefied layer, moves faster than the liquefied part, and the liquefied part left behind the earth block goes down as a debris flow. Laboratory experiments confirmed the existence of this process, and they also examined the arrival distances of both earth-block and debris-flow under various merging angles into the river channel having various inclinations and cross-sectional shapes. A numerical simulation model that represents the solid part of earth-mass by a bundle of cohesive cylinders is developed. These cylinders are supported on the liquefied layer, and the liquefied layer is successively produced by the fracture of lower water saturated part of cylinders.
