AB  - This paper presents a description of the devastation from an earthquake in the Finisterre Ranges of Papua New Guinea and the succession of events comprising huge landslides, formation of debris dams, high rainfall, and washouts that have transported hundreds of thousands of cubic metres of debris. With bridges destroyed and the need to re-establish them, the hydraulic and morphologic considerations are described, together with the measures used to arrive at designs that would handle future natural flooding as distinct from further major catastrophic avulsions from earthquake-generated landslides. This paper, while a case study, attempts to present the scale of problems from earthquake-related debris flows and procedures which can be applied to design highway crossings in the face of such catastrophes.
