FX  - Grand County, Utah and the Utah State Division of Forestry, Fire, and Lands (FFL), especially FFL administrator Gary Cornell, provided invaluable heavy equipment and personnel to improve access routes and remove overburden. James Kirkland, David Gillette, and Martha Hayden of the Utah Geological Survey provided permits. We are grateful to neighboring Arches National Park, especially Jim Webster, for their help. BBB and RDS extend their gratitude to the Department of Geological Sciences, the Museum of Paleontology, and the College of Physical and Mathematical Sciences at Brigham Young University for financial support of this project. Generous grants from the David Jones Foundation supported student and field and lab work. A grant from the Dinosaur Society to BBB is gratefully acknowledged. Nikki Anderson, Anne Dangerfield, Mark Nolte and Parker Valora helped collect data and digitize the quarry map. Teagan Tomlin assisted with graphics. Volunteers at the Museum of Western Colorado and the Stewart Museum prepared most of the thousands of bones and we thank them for their efforts. We especially thank volunteers Gary Anderson, Don Boden, Bonnie Carter, Lynn Farber, Kay Fredette, Gaylord Hedrick, Sandy Hood, Larry Marshal, and Mel Moyer, Ralph Nash and Wait Williams for their dedication to the project. Special honors are due Jeff Higgerson who worked tirelessly and cheerfully collecting at DW over a period of many years. We recognize Lynn Ottinger for his discovery of iguanodontid teeth that piqued James A. Jensen's interest in the site. We thank two anonymous reviewers of the manuscript and J. Keith Rigby Sr. for their help in improving this paper. Finally, we dedicate this paper to the memory of James A. Jensen who mentored BBB and RDS and introduced us to the wonders of Dalton Wells in 1978.
